File Sharing with Permissions in Active Directory
Requirement

Windows Server with Active Directory Domain Services

Domain Users created

Client machine joined to domain

Logged in as Domain Administrator

PART 1: Create Folder for Sharing
Step 1: Create Folder

Login to Domain Controller

Create a folder
Example:

C:\SharedData

PART 2: Configure NTFS (Security) Permissions
Step 1: Open Folder Properties

Right-click SharedData

Click Properties

Go to Security tab

Step 2: Add Domain Users / Groups

Click Edit

Click Add

Enter:

Domain Users


Click Check Names

Click OK

Step 3: Set Permissions

Assign permissions based on requirement:

Read Only Access

Allow: Read & Execute

Allow: List folder contents

Allow: Read

Read and Write Access

Allow: Modify

Allow: Read & Execute

Allow: Write

Click Apply and OK

PART 3: Configure Share Permissions
Step 1: Share the Folder

Right-click SharedData

Click Properties

Go to Sharing tab

Click Advanced Sharing

Check Share this folder

Share Name:

SharedData

Step 2: Set Share Permissions

Click Permissions

Remove Everyone (optional)

Add:

Domain Users


Set permissions:

Read → Read access

Modify → Change access

Click OK

Important Note

Final permission = Lowest permission between NTFS and Share permissions

PART 4: Access Shared Folder from Client Machine
Step 1: Login from Client

Login to client PC using domain user account

Step 2: Access Share

Press Windows + R

Enter:

\\SERVERNAME\SharedData


Press Enter

PART 5: Verify Permissions
Test Read-Only User

Can open files

Cannot create or delete files

Test Read-Write User

Can create files

Can modify and delete files

PART 6: Best Practice (Using Groups)
Create Security Groups

Open Active Directory Users and Computers

Create Groups:

File_Read
File_Modify

Assign Permissions

Assign permissions to Groups

Add users to groups

Avoid assigning permissions directly to users

Conclusion

File Sharing with proper permissions has been successfully configured in Active Directory environment.
